I think there are three dimensions to this.

The first one is "if it's not tested, it's broken" -- the fact that nobody durably steps up to set up or fix the postgres tests in CI, so it's a constant burden for QA. This can potentially be fixed by having all those people who care about postgres support step up to make sure it's properly tested in upstream CI.

The second dimension (as voiced by mordred during the TC meeting at http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/tc/2017/tc.2017-02-14-20.01.log.html#l-349 ) is that relying on a wide abstraction prevents us from leveraging specific features or optimizations in a given DB implementation. To make up my mind on that I'd like to have more specific examples of desirable features or optimizations that we are prevented from taking advantage of.

The third dimension is that the abstraction fails to isolate us from implementation-specific issues, so supporting multiple types of databases has a development cost -- supporting less options would make the code more simple and robust. Here again, some specific examples would help clarify what people have in mind. As Michael said in his comment, he is available to address them.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2017-02-17 15:19:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Some concrete things that I know I gave up on because getting things sorted in an appropriate way requires also considering the pg position.

1) Consistent utf8 in display names. Right now mysql based deployments use 3 bytes because we force all the entire db into utf8 mode (with a performance penalty a bunch of other places) because we pass mysql_charset='utf8' on sql migrate.

Literally have no idea what's going on in the pg space, its not specified so I assume we're using system defaults, which is going to very between environments. If utf8 was used, then pg would be 4 bytes, which is different again.

2) case search is different between mysql and pg. So a select * where a='foo' on mysql matches 'Foo', 'FOO', 'foo', on pg it just matches 'foo'. This means that you end up with the ability to have 'Foo' and 'foo' on pg, but effectively not on mysql, which again leaks through the API.


These are the kinds of edges that make for subtle bugs, and happen when the db acts differently."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2017-02-17 15:46:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> Right now mysql based deployments use 3 bytes because we force all the entire db into utf8 mode (with a performance penalty a bunch of other places) because we pass mysql_charset='utf8' on sql migrate.

If I'm reading https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/charset-unicode-utf8.html correctly, that's only if the character datatype is CHAR, not VARCHAR.   Looked at a few tables in nova, glance, etc. and they appear to use VARCHAR, so a unicode symbol in the normal 0-127 space should be using one byte per character.

> Literally have no idea what's going on in the pg space, its not specified so I assume we're using system defaults, which is going to very between environments. 

yes this is whatever was set up, but also the CREATE DATABASE as set up in whatever installer is used can set the charset at the database level.

> If utf8 was used, then pg would be 4 bytes, which is different again.

PG stores utf-8 correctly so for the vast majority of characters it will be one byte  https://www.postgresql.org/docs/9.0/static/multibyte.html

> case search is different between mysql and pg. So a select * where a='foo' on mysql matches 'Foo', 'FOO', 'foo', on pg it just matches 'foo'. This means that you end up with the ability to have 'Foo' and 'foo' on pg, but effectively not on mysql, which again leaks through the API.

The issue is that MySQL uses case insensitive collations by default, with the option to establish case sensitive collations (https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/case-sensitivity.html) but I don't think Openstack is making use of these.  Postgresql supports collations as well but none of them are "case insensitive"; on PG, you typically need to use the LOWER() function to get case insensitive comparisons.

So given that, this is an area where it is impossible for any "abstraction layer" to hide this up front without specific instructions; for this to be automatic without the programmer ever having to know about it, it would mean that if one used SQLAlchemy on Postgresql only, it would force all character comparisons inside of lower(x) so that in case that application were ever plugged into MySQL with default collations, it would behave the same.  I hope it's obvious that this would be a ridiculous design decision.   

So if case-insensitive string comparisons are a requirement, the abstraction layers must be used such that this is expected.  It is possible to create a string comparator that ensures all lower case string comparisons in all cases, and additionally can take the MySQL collation into account so that it doesn't emit the lower() function if unnecessary, as this will make indexes unusable.  On Postgresql, an INDEX that requires case insensitive comparisons also needs to be made using a functional index that specifies lower() (a feature MySQL doesn't have).

Now if this is really an issue Openstack needs to get into, e.g. enforce case-insensitive string comparisons by default everywhere without the programmer ever having to know about it, I can build abstractions into oslo.db that will do this across MySQL / Postgresql that will even build out the PG indexes with lower case functions built in.  This can be supported if needed.   Alternatively, case-sensitive collations can be set up on the MySQL side (but for existing schemas this requires a mass ALTER that rewrites data and will be time consuming).   That is, one side or the other has to be nudged to match and the methods by which that occurs are very different.    But certainly I can get oslo.db to "hide" all of this if we really care - it's just it would either happen for the String type everywhere (dangerous as it would likely cause regressions somewhere), or if only specific openstack application wanted to "opt in" to this change then we'd need to have them use a new type like CollatingString() or something that refers to the new behavior.'}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2017-02-20 15:25:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

So I am wondering if we actually need a three pronged approach here:

a) We make a resolution about what we "support" upstream (i.e. talk about the deprecation tag, and the implications of that tag).
We should discuss how we stop doing things, and ask for help around certainly things.

b) Talk about a resolution that says supporting "everything badly" is not the correct approach, we sometimes need to pick preferred choices to make progress, such as picking what code is gated on. A more general statement of advice / intent.

c) Merge a resolution saying we are deprecating PostgresSQL due to lack of upstream testing. Help is needed to decide the way forward. Noting that deprecation is not a one way street, its also a cry for help. Our current stack is proving too hard to support non-mysql like things, we are frankly struggling to support all the mysql like things properly.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2017-03-03 21:20:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> Merge a resolution saying we are deprecating PostgresSQL due to lack of upstream testing. Help is needed to decide the way forward.

The lack of upstream testing is, in my opinion, putting too much emphasis on that part of this. Again, postgresql was not failing at a high rate in the gate jobs. The reason we removed that specific job was because it was no longer unique except for the database backend and we wanted to make room for testing other jobs. We could certainly still test with postgresql if we enabled that in one of our other jobs, e.g. we have the single and multi-node jobs, we could run mysql in one and postgresql in the other, or run postgresql in the ceph job (which isn't voting because it was running on everything and failing at a high rate with little help to fix it - and again, ceph is a highly deployed backend for openstack so you'd think if we care about support statements, we'd make it a priority to fix that job).

Anyway, I just don't want to have it sound like we're removing support because it was always broken, because it wasn't."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2017-03-07 10:19:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

After yesterday's forum meeting I'm inclined toward not doing this for a few different reasons but the issue that changed my mind the most was:

We expend a great deal of effort insuring that the tooling people create to use the OpenStack APIs continue to work across upgrades and changes. Microversions. Interoperability guidelines.

There are deployments out there which are using postgresql and have OpenStack specific tooling to manage it. The argument that there could be database migration tools to go from postgresql to mysql don't necessarily apply to the tooling and infrastructure that people have created to manage their database(s).

Beyond that, the reasons put forward for why we should do this don't seem that killer relative to the reasons not to:

* We're not testing postgres in the gate; we can fix that pretty easily. This doesn't mean we need to have double the number of tests. It means we could have a mix. We don't need a huge load of extra effort here.
* The issues with collation aren't something we should mask by using a database that unifies the behavior. We should have code that is explicit about how it should work, irrespective of the database. Those kinds of weirdnesses need to be exposed not hidden.
* The limitation of keystone being difficult to reach rolling upgrades if it has to talk to multiple databases sounds far more like a thing that should be fixed in keystone rather than a data. Or at least that limitation needs to be far more explained if it is to be used as part of the justification.
* Being able to do db engine specific things once we only offer one sounds like an invitation to YAGNI and over engineering. There's little compelling evidence that we need the level of special behavior. In fact the evidence (at least from this week) suggests that we need to be more generic about data storage.

And finally, using a database abstraction layer like sqlalchemy is what might be described as a commonly accepted good, in part because of the reasons above: people often choose a database in their environment independently from the suite of tools they use to do stuff. Moving away from that goodness strikes me a serious step back.

If the cost was huge, sure kill it because there isn't a champion, but I don't think we've established that the cost is high relative to the benefits. Matt R. made it pretty clear we can just turn it on in the gate, so why not?"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2017-05-15 11:04:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2017-05-15 11:06:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I am worried that this is developer-focused at the expense of operator correctness: As an operator, I care most of all about data correctness.
One major benefit PostgreSQL has been providing to the community  (if it isn't disabled in the gate for no apparent valid reason), is to discover incorrect and sloppy SQL programming, e.g. sane & defaults.

If PostgreSQL is to be removed, all MySQL gate checks/tests should be reconfigured to use proper sane configurations.

Not doing so is a long-term dangerous deviation away from correctness towards increased incorrectness, which can be very costly for operators.

I can only support deprecating PostgreSQL if there is an equal commit by the developer community towards making *all* MySQL tests safe and sane, to discover at least some of the incorrectness that PostgreSQL does."}, {'account_id': 11526, 'date': '2017-05-16 09:50:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

As a useful case in point to very aptly illustrate my concern, look at review 427667 ( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/427667/ ).  Incorrect SQL syntax caught by PostgreSQL.  The bug in question seems to have caused some more push towards disabling PostgreSQL checks: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-February/111357.html

What's interesting to me is how some people are considering this a matter of "PostgreSQL support", when it is more accurately a matter of using correct SQL syntax.  Note that the referenced review which reinforced a "let's drop PostgreSQL" rough consensus, states: "This works on mysql with unpredicable result, but don't for other RDBMS."

To be very clear: "unpredictable results" is IMO not production-grade code.

The current momentum thus seems to be towards devs simply preferring to avoid seeing a bug due to incorrect syntax as above, i.e. very literally in favor of "mysql with unpredictable result".  I find this a very unfortunate way forward for the project. The cost of catching incorrect SQL syntax early is so tremendously much less than once in production all over the planet, it shouldn't even have to be stated.'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2017-05-16 12:01:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

@Martin Millnert I totally hear you about the "group by", for many years, I've been all about the "group by" thing as evidence of MySQL's relational bankruptcy.  But.  That is really the one really major relational failing in MySQL right now that we can single out as completely incorrect.   In modern MySQL there aren't any other big ones I'm thinking of - for that particular thing, I'm all for turning on ONLY_FULL_GROUP_BY for oslo.db's SQL mode setting (https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/sql-mode.html#sqlmode_only_full_group_by).   The rest of what tends to be mediocre in MySQL is the crappy type support, such as allowance of things like invalid dates and implicit coercions between strings and numbers, and the poor query planner, but these are less severe issues and the typing issues are largely worked out by SQLAlchemy.

but as far as "unpredictable results", that's the GROUP BY thing and I'm not sure what else.   It's of limited impact and with a SQL mode setting we can catch the rest of those.  

FYI this should not be taken as an endorsement of the "drop postgresql" idea nor should this disclaimer be taken as an endorsement of the "keep postgresql" position on my part.  I know I usually have excessively virulent positions on things but this one I'm not too committed either way.  I do think oslo.db should keep around the idea of "we work on other databases" within its codebase, as first off, we still work on SQLite anyway within test suites and keeping a "DB-agnostic" stance allows things like NDB support to be a lot easier to implement.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-05-16 13:20:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Rollcall-Vote-1

I continue to think this is the wrong approach. Yes, it is reasonable for us to update the docs to reflect reality. But outlining a set of guidelines for how to migrate away from postgres is kind of like giving up. I would prefer that we outline a set of guidelines that allow us to correct reality.

In my comments on patchset 3 I said, "We expend a great deal of effort insuring that the tooling people create to use the OpenStack APIs continue to work across upgrades and changes. Microversions. Interoperability guidelines. There are deployments out there which are using postgresql and have OpenStack specific tooling to manage it." I continue to think that's an important issue.

So too is another thing I said on the same ps, "And finally, using a database abstraction layer like sqlalchemy is what might be described as a commonly accepted good, in part because of the reasons above: people often choose a database in their environment independently from the suite of tools they use to do stuff. Moving away from that goodness strikes me a serious step back."

So rather than documenting that "oh by the way we've actually been mysql oriented all along, we just made a mistake in not making that clear" we should instead:

* document the need for the suggested warning in the docs about lack of gate support and drive that forward
* document the steps required to get that warning removed (i.e., what's required to get good gate support)
* document the value, with regard to database abstractions and SQL robustness, of supporting at least two databases
* give this resolution to the board as an example of one of the areas in which there is an easy win for additional contribution

It may simply be because I am old that I don't think this is the same as the rabbit/qpid situation, but I don't (see the quotes above from ps3).

Summit made it pretty clear that we as the TC need to be a bit more activist with delivering some requirements to the board. This is an opportunity to start with something that is relatively easy to explain and relatively easy to get some benefit from. After all the real guts of the problem is "we need to turn on a few more tests". That's not that big of a deal is it? If it is, then there's a thing to fix.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2017-05-16 13:41:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

First: Opinions on the relative merits of MySQL vs. PG are not particularly helpful to the discussion. Nothing about this resolution is or ever has been suggesting that either MySQL or PG are superior or inferior to each other. The only result that will EVER come of such discussions is as best a flame war and a worst a meh. Both databases have pros and cons. Both databases have vibrant and active user communities. Both are used for enough real-world use cases that attempting to dismiss either as fundamentally flawed in any way is silly. I'd like to ask that we do our best to refrain from letting comments colored with such implications through, as they introduce flame-bait into an already delicate and difficult discussion.

It's not just about turning on tests, it's also about ensuring we have enough resources who understand PG well to be involved in development and design work. That said, I agree that it's a great opportunity to put together a specific request to the board.

My personal take away from the Forum is that there is more work to be done to be able to frame next steps. One of the outcomes we're considering is full deprecation and removal. But in order to fully consider that, we must also consider and characterize the cost of not doing so - otherwise it's impossible to weigh the costs against each other or provide people with vested interests the opportunity to pay the costs.

History tells us that we'll find a lack of interest in such costs, as they are not product features but instead firmly in the commons where we tend to be massively under-resourced. However, I'm ready and willing to be pleasantly surprised."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2017-05-16 14:37:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

Given that reduced scope, I'm OK with this approach."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2017-05-16 14:50:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> First: Opinions on the relative merits of MySQL vs. PG are not
 > particularly helpful to the discussion. Nothing about this
 > resolution is or ever has been suggesting that either MySQL or PG
 > are superior or inferior to each other. The only result that will
 > EVER come of such discussions is as best a flame war and a worst a
 > meh. Both databases have pros and cons. Both databases have vibrant
 > and active user communities. Both are used for enough real-world
 > use cases that attempting to dismiss either as fundamentally flawed
 > in any way is silly. I'd like to ask that we do our best to refrain
 > from letting comments colored with such implications through, as
 > they introduce flame-bait into an already delicate and difficult
 > discussion.
 
I agree with this. I am, if read carefully at least, not attempting to comment on the relative merits of either engine, merely that whichever is used, all correctness things possible has to be turned on by default, with the very clear purpose and intent to slap devs in the face early, rather than allow bugs through due to complacency. I'd bet that the typical issues that devs will face will be of O(10) categories, and I'm afraid that's just something devs have to be able to deal with.  My very factual observation regarding PG is that, 1) it is essentially configured like this out of the box, 2) thus, its removal opens up a "hole" in the QA chain, not covered by careless MySQL settings.

 > It's not just about turning on tests, it's also about ensuring we
 > have enough resources who understand PG well to be involved in
 > development and design work.

1) On the amount of resources -- with a community-wide standardization on sane defaults optimized towards maximum data safety/correctness, something like 90% of the general differences between disappear, doesn't it?
2) There was another comment on the merits of intently avoiding to do engine-specific optimizations as well.

> That said, I agree that it's a great opportunity to put together a specific request to the board.

The entire argumentation around this subject is damaging if not coupled with efforts to actually up the level of data correctness. It seems to me then to be a great need for improving MySQL sanity across the board regardless of path forward. I find that to be the actual biggest source of pain here: deferred / latent bugs.

 > My personal take away from the Forum is that there is more work to
 > be done to be able to frame next steps. One of the outcomes we're
 > considering is full deprecation and removal. But in order to fully
 > consider that, we must also consider and characterize the cost of
 > not doing so - otherwise it's impossible to weigh the costs against
 > each other or provide people with vested interests the opportunity
 > to pay the costs.
 
100% support for an objective evaluation, with argument that hold up to "the 5 why's" or similar scrutiny.  I think the conversation is decent and constructive so far.

 > History tells us that we'll find a lack of interest in such costs,
 > as they are not product features but instead firmly in the commons
 > where we tend to be massively under-resourced. However, I'm ready
 > and willing to be pleasantly surprised.

Yeah, similar issues have surfaced in the industry w.r.t. eg openssl, an assumed underfunded commons, and we all know how that went. It's not that much of a stretch to claim DB dev-support in OpenStack is a similar sort of commons that actually require some level of funding. Perhaps foundation funding members would be OK with commonly funding such a resource through the foundation.


I think it is very premature to conclude that deprecating multi-engine support is something that should be done before there is progress on the more important concerns raised here. Note also that "deprecating postgresql" is discriminatory, as there is support for eg. SQLite which for the arguments given, to make any sense at all, should also be deprecated. I feel vaguely bad for belabouring this, but I feel obliged to vote (and comment) with my conscience and react to what I see happening here, which is not actually the same as what the commit message says is happening.

From my perspective what this is is an effort to move us to a state where mysql (and derivatives) is not just the default but the only database used by OpenStack. If that really is the goal, then the commit message and the document should say so and our votes should be about that.

That, however, should not be the goal and should not be what this document (or my version at I212ac603279e495866411760727ef904df849325 ) should do. Instead we should:

* document the warning statement about the level of testing for PostgreSQL in (as both documents suggest)
* leave open future opportunities for different database back ends

This latter point seems to me especially critical if we want to ensure that the door remains open for innovation™ at the persistence layer including the ideas about new SQL as suggested by this thread [1].

This document, as currently formed, represents a bias about the future that I can't support but I _can_ support making a clear statement that the documentation needs to change. Ideally we wouldn't need to do that (and based on comments from some people it is not clear that we really need to, but I'm willing to accept the stance that we should for the time being) but reality is as it is.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-May/117018.html"}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2017-05-21 17:23:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

This is not at all what I was expecting as the output from our discussion in the meeting last week.

My understanding from that was that we were going to leave out any discussion of the future, leaving differences of opinion on the value of the database abstraction layer for another time and _solely_ report that postgresql is not getting attention and elucidate the two (of three) factors on which we could agree (items 1 and 3 listed by Sean at http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/tc/2017/tc.2017-06-06-20.00.log.html#l-88 )

What we have here instead is pretty much the "mysql is what we intend to support henceforth" document of which I'm very much not in favor.

As promised I'm not going to -1 this, because it's not do or die for me, but I do not think this captures the outcome of the meeting and I do not think this decision is really to the benefit of the community so I hope people will go back and review the log a bit more closely: http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/tc/2017/tc.2017-06-06-20.00.log.html'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2017-06-12 18:33:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

Chris, to be honest I'm a bit lost on the outcome of the TC discussion. While rereading it is indeed somewhat the consensus that point 1 (warning in the doc) and 3 (we should collect more data) was accepted, as well as a rewording of point 2 that would say something like "gather data on how costly it would be for users to migrate from postgresql to mysql".  I somewhat jumped the gun by rewording that into "embrace contributions" (which is not only collect data about the cost but also make the cost less expensive for those who want to do it). Are you specifically concerned about this move ? I"m fine with rewording it into "lets collect the cost (not sure how, I need a suggestion for that) and then reevaluate this somewhen in the future".

I intentionally ignored the "but suse does this" part of the discussion because I think it was a red herring (and I think I can say that because I'm a SUSE employee and am somewhat watching the postgresql / mysql research). 

Here's my suggestion: would you be +1 by removing the section "There is also an impact on future work..." and  "We should embrace contributions.." ?

it somehow feels unsatisfying to me (to explicitly warn users that when they want an upstream-compatible deployment to chose mysql but allow vendors to choose something else and report aggregated data.. as if vendors would like to choose something that is not-upstreams preferred choice and prefer to do an uphill battle.. anyway).'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-06-12 21:27:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Sorry things are unclear Dirk, it's not surprising there are multiple interpretations of the outcome of the meeting: we identified some fairly fundamental disagreements. The gist I got was that we would focus on simply listing the actions that need to be taken with regard to postgresql and leave it at that as we currently did not have agreement on much of anything else.

So in terms of changing the document so that it more on those terms I would suggest at least some of:

* reverting the title of the commit to being about postgresql
* remove the second paragraph
* collapse the 3rd and 4th paragraph into something more concise
* do the two things you suggested:
** remove the "There is also an impact" section
** remove the embrace contributions section, or change it so that what is being embraced is contribution on using databases generically, well
* s/is not first class supported/is not currently first class supported/ (maybe with a "because we don't currently have resources" caveat)
* s/and has never been// (in the same paragraph)

That would declare the state of postgresql and inform people that there are risks (right now) if they are using postgresql while still leaving our options open for the future. Sure, this document sets nothing in stone, but it telegraphs an intent, and I do not think it is useful for a project as long lived and diverse as OpenStack to constrain technology as fundamental as the database layer.

But again, I'm not voting. I'm reiterating my position because the current version of this document suggests that it wasn't as evident from the meeting as I thought. And based on conversations I've had with others, it's not just me, so I feel obliged to make sure it is visible.

Thanks again for taking on this set of revisions, Dirk.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2017-06-12 21:47:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Declare plainly the current state of PostgreSQL in OpenStack

This declares the current state of OpenStack's database support
explaining the impact of perceived support of PostgreSQL.

It advises concrete steps to take in order to avoid a false
impression of having a sustaining PostgreSQL support available.

Co-Authored-By: Dirk Mueller <dirk@dmllr.de>

Change-Id: I332cef8ec4539520adcf37c6d2ea11488289fcfd

commit_message:
use synchronized decorator from neutron-lib

neutron-lib contains the synchronized lock decorator and neutron is
removing it's implementation I729da348e340509f2d09f8a6436716e2398f1583

This patch uses the decorator from neutron-lib rather than neutron.

Change-Id: Iaf2ce2e339471c91fa64047942c0bb385dd224ee

commit_message:
Update node failed

Update node failed via dashboard.
The mesg: There was an error submitting the form. Please try again.
The detailed message of failure : Exception Value: 'cluster_id'.
Refer to url : https://docs.openstack.org/senlin/latest/user/nodes.html#updating-a-node.
At least now we know that we can update name, profile, role and metadata of node ,
but can not update cluster that node updated belongs to.
For details, see bug below.

Change-Id: Ie871a59cc6a6533e35b1e8828cd980c68d33eae1
Closes-Bug: #1707120

[{'created': '2017-07-20 01:18:32.000000000', 'message': 'Enable some off-by-default checks

Some of the available checks are disabled by default, like:
[H106] Don’t put vim configuration in source files
[H203] Use assertIs(Not)None to check for None

commit_message:
Enable some off-by-default checks

Some of the available checks are disabled by default, like:
[H106] Don’t put vim configuration in source files
[H203] Use assertIs(Not)None to check for None

Change-Id: I553460a231ee27b63220c1540b39fd213e79e032

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-07-20 00:58:40.000000000', 'message': 'The parameter "fields" is lack in call to self._make_bgp_peer_dict.

If "fields" vaule is not "None" in the function
"get_bgp_peers_by_bgp_speaker", this value should
be put into the called function "self._make_bgp_peer_dict(x)".

Change-Id: Icfb50a4ae59f3008c81bd39bd16c8827841b33d7
'}]
commit_message:
The parameter "fields" is lack in call to self._make_bgp_peer_dict.

If "fields" vaule is not "None" in the function
"get_bgp_peers_by_bgp_speaker", this value should
be put into the called function "self._make_bgp_peer_dict(x)".

Change-Id: Icfb50a4ae59f3008c81bd39bd16c8827841b33d7

in Pike[1].

Hi Kevin, thanks for the update.
After I recheck this issue, I find that transient switching loop may not exist...
The fail_mode of br-int, br-eth0 and br-ex are secure, which means that when node reboot or OpenvSwitch restart, there will no normal flow in these bridges so no packets can pass these bridges.
The normal flow in br-int will not make switching loop because there is no normal flow in br-eth0 and br-ex. Normal flow and drop flow are added in br-eth0 then br-ex. It seems transient switching loop can not happen.
am I missing anything?'}, {'account_id': 8655, 'date': '2017-07-27 07:55:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2017-07-28 07:24:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2017-07-28 07:26:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Yeah, if the physical bridges are fail-mode secure, they wouldn't act like a learning switch either. Maybe there isn't a loop here then.

@Jesse, abandon the patch and mark the bug invalid if that's the case."}, {'account_id': 10518, 'date': '2017-07-28 07:32:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I created this bug because I run into transient switching loop in our environment some time ago.
I will check carefully next time if the problem show up.
Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 10518, 'date': '2017-07-28 07:33:47.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fix potential transient switching loop in br-int

Avoid setting up default table in integration bridge before
the physical bridges are setup to drop traffic. This avoids
potential switching loops.

Closes-Bug: #1682805
Change-Id: I8853ba5ad1c795de22de1e419598f138636d220b

commit_message:
Remove obsolete cache_data from Stack

This is no longer required as the convergence 'lightweight stack' used for
checking individual resources has now merged with the other code paths: in
every case intrinsic functions are resolved using the data about resources
stored in StackDefinition and accessed via ResourceProxy.

Change-Id: I41cf21c8e1babe819b4b6c668749ed5915ae3b54

commit_message:
Enable some off-by-default checks

Some of the available checks are disabled by default, like:
[H106] Don’t put vim configuration in source files
[H203] Use assertIs(Not)None to check for None

Change-Id: Iadb49e002b788793c2b9ef5605f247fe8e47eb2f

commit_message:
fix alignment of toc tree items in sidebar

The global toctree showing the document structure uses a different
HTML mix than the in-page toctree, so we have to express the padding
differently.

Change-Id: Iee79924d893180c8233a6b345f9f2143a7840324
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Refactor project tree

Old project tree had everything mixed up
in different locations. Not to mention
that actual REST controllers resided in
package that's name did not reflect the content.

Reorganized the tree to be more predictable
and easier to maintain.

Change-Id: Ic9acc80a4cf7416394702d43141c96953c03beea
